Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new Federal Reserve Board members gives people in America – and the U.S. Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future direction.
The obvious, first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to fail so badly in its most important mandate – ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional self-examination is certainly warranted.
Yet while interest rate policy makes headlines, the Fed is now mainly significant as a financial regulator.
A further major question is therefore whether it will use its immense power to advance climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, deny credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, require banks to grant credit only to companies with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit towards desired alternatives.
Furthermore, it could decide to explicitly take up its regulatory activity in the name of equality or ethnic justice by requiring banks to specify where and to whom loans are granted, who is hired and who is fired, and so on.
Yet before we turn to the question of in which direction the regulation of the Fed will or should move, it is first necessary to clarify the serious failure of the Fed.
In 2008, the U.S. government made a fateful decision: financial institutions could still largely obtain money for risky investments through the sale of short-term, liquidity-vulnerable debt securities, but swarms of new regulatory agencies would now assess the riskiness of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory agencies would no longer overlook massive chunks of subprime mortgages in the banks' balance sheets.
Yet over the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the regulatory army of the Fed never once asked itself what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually struck in early 2020, the Fed discarded its "Never again" promises from 2008 and intervened to an even greater extent.
In March, it became clear that commercial banks were unable to act as intermediaries on the market for ordinary U.S. Treasury securities.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The market corrections would have been simple, but obvious reforms were postponed for a long time.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never happened.
Additionally, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported the prices of corporate bonds by essentially providing a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the U.S. Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector rescue package - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in 2020, with the "Powell put" - among other things - an explicit floor for the prices of corporate bonds was introduced.
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
Lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply put out every new fire with another flood of money.
The problem, however, lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why bother to make an effort and use cash reserves or balance sheet space for purchases at falling prices, provide liquidity, or treat a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will anyway outperform everyone and pocket the profits.
Why issue company stocks when you can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when it comes to buying dubious papers, if their value is guaranteed by another "whatever-it-takes promise" from the Fed during bad times?
No wonder that America is sinking into debt.
All assume that taxpayers will bear the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, government bonds, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for their turn to be rescued by Uncle Sam's bailout efforts.
Yet every new crisis requires even more transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into rescue operations, and people will not be happy with billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up in a big fire – and the fire station will be burned down.
In 2008, regulators and lawmakers at least recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, people indulged only in self-congratulation regarding the rescue operations.
The very Fed, which failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages in 2008 just as it failed to foresee the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests with regard to "climate risks," will certainly overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The Fed's regulators do not even ask the questions about the aforementioned events.
And although jargon about "networks," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define the "systemic" risk, apart from it becoming a catch-all term that grants regulators sweeping power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to foresee risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that massive debts can always be paid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always stands behind mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire station is put to the test.
A better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it claims that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit few Americans.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
An immense effort to comply with regulations presents a major obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is meaningless.
Regulatory provisions are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted side effects or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires no prophetic skills from regulatory authorities.
The Fed scandalously stopped companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sector, which could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits itself to the salvation of the planet and the redress of injustices, the Fed should first be held accountable for how poorly it has fulfilled its fundamental duty of protecting the financial system.
